node.text:
Once upon a time, I had cravings for sugary foods like granola bars or muffins as soon as I got up in the morning, but those cravings vanished after I began this habit. 

Now I crave whole and satisfying foods instead. 

Starting my day with a healthy action sets me up for success for the rest of the day and is a reminder that my health comes first.

Please tag your friends below to share this tip. This ritual is just too easy not to do – so drink up and start each day with this healthy habit!

Click the link in my bio to learn more!

node.text:
Even though we’ve made tremendous progress…the truth is that big companies just don’t change fast enough.

I believe we deserve to live in a world where our products can be made without weird – and nasty – ingredients.

Is that too much to ask?

Apparently so. Because we are so far away it’s crazy.

So, I decided to take matters into my own hands.

I launched @truvani and we have one main goal: eliminate nasty ingredients from all daily-use products.

We started with supplements. Now we are creating personal care products. 

Visit Truvani.com to learn more.

I know you’ll like them. And when you see the ingredient labels, you’ll LOVE THEM.

node.text:
Here’s a little peek inside the Food Babe Kitchen cookbook: 

You’ll find this Ultimate “No-No” List of food additives to avoid on page 9. 

The ingredients listed here are what I’ve identified as the most important ingredients to avoid in processed foods, because they’re associated with negative health issues. The link in my bio has a complete description of each and why I’ve flagged them!

If a product contains any of these additives, try finding an alternative or make the food at home, from scratch.

Many people assume that everything allowed in our food has been proven safe to eat and that the FDA is ensuring the safety of all ingredients.

Sadly, that is not the reality.

The FDA hasn’t reviewed the safety of thousands of food additives, and isn’t even aware that many of them exist.

That means that dozens of products sitting in your kitchen right now could be filled with questionable additives.

It’s up to you to know what the specific ingredients are that you should watch out for on every label. 

The best way to avoid these additives is to stop eating processed and fast food, by cooking with real food at home.

Food Babe Kitchen will help you get off of processed food in an easy and delicious way. 

It has over 100 recipes to replace all those processed foods you are eating. 

There are even recipes for a healthy Chick-Fil-A Sandwich and Doritos. 

Save this list “No-No” List to your phone and tag your friends below to share!

Yesterday if you saw my video about the new Organic Reese’s and Hershey’s Chocolate...they are still making their original versions with controversial chemicals. I can’t support companies like Hershey’s who have been poisoning us for years with ingredients like TBHQ and still won’t remove it from Reese’s Peanut Butter Cups even after proving that it’s completely unnecessary by creating an organic version without it. Shouldn’t they go ahead and remove these ingredients from all of their products now?

Continue voting with your dollars and support companies who are doing the right things! 

A few of my favorite organic chocolate brands include @HuKitchen, @jjscocomels, and @altereco_foods. 

When shopping for chocolate, here are some of the top ingredients to avoid:

❌ TBHQ: A synthetic preservative that may harm the immune system, promotes allergies and is linked increased incidence of tumors in animal studies.

❌ CORN SYRUP: A heavily processed form of sugar typically made from the starch of GMO corn.

❌ ARTIFICIAL FLAVORS: Chemical mixtures produced by fractional distillation and chemical manipulation of various chemicals like crude oil or coal tar. 

❌ NATURAL FLAVORS: Proprietary mixtures that make food taste irresistible so that you keep coming back for more. 

❌ PGPR: A cheap emulsifier used to replace more expensive cocoa butter.

node.text:
Pasta night doesn’t need to be an unhealthy dinner full of refined flour, powdered wood, inflammatory oils and sugar. And you don’t need to make it all from scratch either! 

Here’s how to step up your game on your next pasta night, without making everything from scratch:

1. Choose chickpea or lentil pasta. Check the ingredients list and make sure it doesn’t contain refined flours or other unnecessary ingredients. Some of my fave organic brands are Chickapea and Tolerant. 

2. Choose organic sauces made with olive oil and no added sugar. Conventional brands are usually made with unhealthy canola oil or soybean oil, which have an inflammatory effect on your body. I like organic pasta sauces by Dave’s Gourmet and Yellow Barn. 

3. Shred your own cheese. Kraft and other popular brands add “cellulose” to their cheese, which is made from wood. This additive has been shown to disrupt gut bacteria, which can lead to weight gain, inflammation and digestive problems.

node.text:
The best expert on your health is YOU.

Right after a health crisis in my early 20s, the first thing I wanted to do was lose weight and get my health on track. At first, I believed what everyone else around me was saying and looked to everyone else for answers. 

I respected authority figures and corporations and followed them blindly, as many people do today.

Organizations such as Weight Watchers told me I could eat virtually anything I wanted as long as I checked the calories or points, carbs, and fat grams. Their advice left me with no energy and feeling hungry all the time.

I outsourced my meals to restaurants such as Subway who told me their food would help me “Eat Fresh” and that I’d lose weight like Jared did if I ate their sandwiches. I believed their marketing, but didn’t see the results I wanted. 

Everything I believed for most of my life was turned upside down as I investigated and looked deeper into who I was trusting. One day it all clicked! 

I could not continue letting the Big Food corporations dictate for me what was healthy. And I most definitely could not trust marketing from corporations who add shady chemicals to their products to help me make decisions about how to eat and take care of myself. 

If you want to be healthy and in shape, you’ve got to take control. No government agency, big food company, or anyone else is going to do it for you. You can’t trust anyone but yourself.

Be fussy about your food choices. Get savvy about what you’re eating. The less a food has been processed, the more it benefits your health. Read labels – not so much the calories or carbs in a product, but the list of ingredients in the food. Eat organic, real food; it’s the best way to protect yourself.

Know anyone who trusts big corporations with their health? Please tag them below to share!

You don’t need to buy supermarket birthday cakes filled with Artificial Colors and other horrible ingredients. The mixes by Duncan Hines and Betty Crocker are just as bad.

Have you seen what’s in those cakes? Swipe left! It’s disgusting.

I don’t eat artificial colors or allow them in my children’s diet at all. I have ZERO tolerance for artificial dyes. This may sound extreme – but there are so many reasons why we shouldn’t be eating them, especially children.

Artificial colors…
🚫Can disrupt the immune system. 
🚫Are man-made in a lab with chemicals derived from petroleum
🚫Require a warning label in other countries outside the US.
🚫Have been banned in countries around the world
🚫Are contaminated with known carcinogens.
🚫Cause an increase in hyperactivity in children.

Even though parties aren’t a daily occurrence, I’m not okay with poisoning my child’s body with artificial colors linked to so many health risks. I want my child to have the best. That is why I will not compromise. 

🌟Click the link in my bio to see all of my best tips & tricks for avoiding artificial colors at parties and celebrations.

If you’re hosting the party - You can make an organic cake from an organic boxed mix, color it naturally, frost it with organic icing and decorate it with non-toxic toppings. It doesn’t need to be complicated or expensive. 

The link in my bio has all the specific details + brand names.
